# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: autotroph
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:autotroph/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-component] In ecology, **abiotic components** or **abiotic factors** are non-living chemical and physical parts of the environment that affect living organisms and the functioning of ecosystems.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors and the phenomena associated with them underpin biology as a whole.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-component] They affect a wide range of species, across all forms of environmental conditions, such as marine or terrestrial animals.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-component] Humans can make or change abiotic factors in a species' environment.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-component] For instance, fertilizers can affect a snail's habitat, or the greenhouse gases which humans utilize can change marine pH levels.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-component] Abiotic components include physical conditions and non-living resources that affect living organisms in terms of growth, maintenance, and reproduction.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-component] Resources are distinguished as substances or objects in the environment required by one organism and consumed or otherwise made unavailable for use by other organisms.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-component] Component degradation of a substance occurs by chemical or physical processes, e.g. hydrolysis.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-component] All non-living components of an ecosystem, such as atmospheric conditions and water resources, are called abiotic components.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-component] In biology, abiotic factors can include water, light, radiation, temperature, humidity, atmosphere, acidity, salinity, precipitation, altitude, minerals, tides, rain, dissolved oxygen nutrients, and soil.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-component] The macroscopic climate often influences each of the above.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-component] Pressure and sound waves may also be considered in the context of marine or sub-terrestrial environments.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors in ocean environments also include aerial exposure, substrate, water clarity, solar energy and tides.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-component] Consider the differences in the mechanics of C3, C4, and CAM plants in regulating the influx of carbon dioxide to the Calvin-Benson Cycle in relation to their abiotic stressors.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-component] C3 plants have no mechanisms to manage photorespiration, whereas C4 and CAM plants utilize a separate PEP carboxylase enzyme to prevent photorespiration, thus increasing the yield of photosynthesis processes in certain high energy environments.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-component] Many Archea require very high temperatures, pressures, or unusual concentrations of chemical substances such as sulfur; this is due to their specialization into extreme conditions.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-component] In addition, fungi have also evolved to survive at the temperature, the humidity, and stability of their environment.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-component] For example, there is a significant difference in access to both water and humidity between temperate rain forests and deserts.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-component] This difference in water availability causes a diversity in the organisms that survive in these areas.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-component] These differences in abiotic components alter the species present by creating boundaries of what species can survive within the environment and influencing competition between two species.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors such as salinity can give one species a competitive advantage over another, creating pressures that lead to speciation and alteration of a species to and from generalist and specialist competitors.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress is essentially unavoidable.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress affects animals, but plants are especially dependent, if not solely dependent, on environmental factors, so it is particularly constraining.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress is the most harmful factor concerning the growth and productivity of crops worldwide.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Research has also shown that abiotic stressors are at their most harmful when they occur together, in combinations of abiotic stress factors.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] The most common of the stressors are the easiest for people to identify, but there are many other, less recognizable abiotic stress factors which affect environments constantly.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Lesser-known stressors generally occur on a smaller scale.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] They include: poor edaphic conditions like rock content and pH levels, high radiation, compaction, contamination, and other, highly specific conditions like rapid rehydration during seed germination.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress, as a natural part of every ecosystem, will affect organisms in a variety of ways.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Although these effects may be either beneficial or detrimental, the location of the area is crucial in determining the extent of the impact that abiotic stress will have.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] The higher the latitude of the area affected, the greater the impact of abiotic stress will be on that area.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] So, a taiga or boreal forest is at the mercy of whatever abiotic stress factors may come along, while tropical zones are much less susceptible to such stressors.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] While abiotic stress may have negative impacts on individual organisms, there are cases where abiotic stress plays an important role in maintaining a healthy ecosystem.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Important ecosystem mechanisms and improved overall stress tolerance may rely on occasional low levels of abiotic stress.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] One example of a situation where abiotic stress plays a constructive role in an ecosystem is in natural wildfires.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Smaller fires are useful in reducing the overall fuel load of an area of forest or prairie.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] By clearing out dead brush and other organic matter, the risk of catastrophic and widespread fire decreases, and the residual ash of smaller fires helps add nutrients back into the soil.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] The observed benefits of these smaller and more controlled fires on land usability and species populations have led to the use of prescribed burning by humans for centuries.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Varying perspectives on the benefits and risks of fire to ecosystems have influenced official policy through history.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Forest Service, initially focused on fire control, changed its policy to one of fire management in 1974, recognizing these fires as a natural part of an ecosystem.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] There is also evidence that a diverse fire history between patches of land within an area has been shown to benefit transitional landscapes between savanna and forest.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Even though it is healthy for an ecosystem, a wildfire can still be considered an abiotic stressor, because it puts stress on individual organisms within the area.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] On the larger scale, though, natural wildfires are positive manifestations of abiotic stress.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] What also needs to be taken into account when looking for benefits of abiotic stress, is that one phenomenon may not affect an entire ecosystem in the same way.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] While a flood will kill most plants living low on the ground in a certain area, if there is rice there, it will thrive in the wet conditions.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Another example of this is in phytoplankton and zooplankton.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] The same types of conditions are usually considered stressful for these two types of organisms.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] They act very similarly when exposed to ultraviolet light and most toxins, but at elevated temperatures the phytoplankton reacts negatively, while the thermophilic zooplankton reacts positively to the increase in temperature.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] The two may be living in the same environment, but an increase in temperature of the area would prove stressful only for one of the organisms.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Lastly, abiotic stress has enabled species to grow, develop, and evolve, through the process of natural selection.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Heritable traits that improve an organism's resiliency under stressed conditions increase the likelihood that the organism will survive and reproduce, enabling it to pass these traits to the next generation.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Both plants and animals have evolved mechanisms allowing them to survive extremes.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] One of the detriments concerning abiotic stress involves farming.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] It has been claimed by one study that abiotic stress causes the most crop loss of any other factor and that most major crops are reduced in their yield by more than 50% from their potential yield.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Because abiotic stress is widely considered a detrimental effect, the research on this branch of the issue is extensive.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] For more information on the harmful effects of abiotic stress, see the sections below on plants and animals.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] A plant's first line of defense against abiotic stress is in its roots.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] If the soil holding the plant is healthy and biologically diverse, the plant will have a higher chance of surviving stressful conditions.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] The plant responses to stress are dependent on the tissue or organ affected by the stress.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] For example, transcriptional responses to stress are tissue or cell specific in roots and are quite different depending on the stress involved.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] One of the primary responses to abiotic stress such as high salinity is the disruption of the Na+/K+ ratio in the cytoplasm of the plant cell.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] High concentrations of Na+, for example, can decrease the capacity for the plant to take up water and also alter enzyme and transporter functions.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Evolved adaptations to efficiently restore cellular ion homeostasis have led to a wide variety of stress tolerant plants.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Facilitation, or the positive interactions between different species of plants, is an intricate web of association in a natural environment.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] In areas of high stress, the level of facilitation is especially high as well.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] This could possibly be because the plants need a stronger network to survive in a harsher environment, so their interactions between species, such as cross-pollination or mutualistic actions, become more common to cope with the severity of their habitat.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Plants also adapt very differently from one another, even from a plant living in the same area.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] When a group of different plant species was prompted by a variety of different stress signals, such as drought or cold, each plant responded uniquely.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Hardly any of the responses were similar, even though the plants had become accustomed to exactly the same home environment.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Serpentine soils (media with low concentrations of nutrients and high concentrations of heavy metals) can be a source of abiotic stress.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Initially, the absorption of toxic metal ions is limited by cell membrane exclusion.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Ions that are absorbed into tissues are sequestered in cell vacuoles.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] This sequestration mechanism is facilitated by proteins on the vacuole membrane.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] An example of plants that adapt to serpentine soil are Metallophytes, or hyperaccumulators, as they are known for their ability to absorbed heavy metals using the root-to-shoot translocation (which it will absorb into shoots rather than the plant itself).
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] They're also extinguished for their ability to absorb toxic substances from heavy metals.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Chemical priming has been proposed to increase tolerance to abiotic stresses in crop plants.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] In this method, which is analogous to vaccination, stress-inducing chemical agents are introduced to the plant in brief doses so that the plant begins preparing defense mechanisms.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Thus, when the abiotic stress occurs, the plant has already prepared defense mechanisms that can be activated faster and increase tolerance.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress mostly affects plants used in agriculture.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Some examples of adverse conditions (which may be caused by climate change) are high or low temperatures, drought, salinity, and toxins.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Elevated global temperatures present a severe bottleneck for crop yields, as heat stress alters membrane fluidity, accelerates destructive transpiration rates, and heavily impairs a plant's overall Water Use Efficiency (WUE).
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] When crops encounter extreme thermal environments during early reproductive or vegetative stages, cellular homeostasis is broken down, causing grain yield reduction and premature leaf senescence.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] To mitigate down-stream damage from overlapping thermal and drought shocks, advanced ex-ante strategies such as physical seed priming or chemical priming agents are applied.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] These priming interventions activate early molecular, enzymatic, and hormonal pre-defense responses within the seed tissue, enabling the plant to maintain higher functional stability and lower oxidative injury when heat stress occurs later in the field environment.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Flooding acts as a compound environmental stressor that is broadly categorized into waterlogging (where only the root system is inundated) and complete submergence (where the entire plant is covered by water).
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] The primary hazard of flooding is gas diffusion restriction, which triggers oxygen starvation (hypoxia or anoxia) in the rhizosphere and alters essential plant hormone signaling networks, such as the regulation between Sub1A and non-Sub1A genotypes in rice.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] To cope with complete submergence, tolerant plants rely on distinct physiological survival strategies.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Furthermore, monitoring maximum quantum yield performance reveals that preserving photosynthetic efficiency during transient flooding stress is paramount to driving rapid physiological recovery once the water recedes.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Soil acidity acts as a sweeping abiotic stress factor on global arable lands, primarily because low pH environments trigger dangerous chemical toxicities dominated by soluble aluminum (Al3+ )and iron, which structurally damage root anatomy and limit basic development.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] High acidity also locks up vital macronutrients, causing severe phosphorus starvation stress that forces plants to aggressively modify their lateral root structures to maximize surface area absorption.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] To remediate heavy-metal-polluted and highly acidic substrates, bioremediation utilizes hyperaccumulator plant traits (metallophytes).
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] These specialized plants successfully survive the toxicity of acidic media by relying on a highly developed root-to-shoot translocation system, which efficiently absorbs and transports toxic ions away from fragile root tissues and sequesters them safely inside the upper shoot vacuoles.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Soil salinization, the accumulation of water-soluble salts to levels that negatively impact plant production, is a global phenomenon affecting approximately 831 million hectares of land.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] More specifically, the phenomenon threatens 19.5% of the world's irrigated agricultural land and 2.1% of the world's non-irrigated (dry-land) agricultural lands.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] High soil salinity content can be harmful to plants because water-soluble salts can alter osmotic potential gradients and consequently inhibit many cellular functions.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Over generations, many plants have mutated and built different mechanisms to counter salinity effects.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] A good combatant of salinity in plants is the hormone ethylene.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Ethylene is known for regulating plant growth and development and dealing with stress conditions.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Many central membrane proteins in plants, such as ETO2, ERS1 and EIN2, are used for ethylene signaling in many plant growth processes.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Mutations in these proteins can lead to heightened salt sensitivity and can limit plant growth.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] The effects of salinity has been studied on *Arabidopsis* plants that have mutated ERS1, ERS2, ETR1, ETR2 and EIN4 proteins.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] These proteins are used for ethylene signaling against certain stress conditions, such as salt and the ethylene precursor ACC is used to suppress any sensitivity to the salt stress.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Phosphorus (P) is an essential macronutrient required for plant growth and development, but it is present only in limited quantities in most of the world's soil.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Plants use P mainly in the form of soluble inorganic phosphates (PO4−−−) but are subject to abiotic stress when there is not enough soluble PO4−−− in the soil.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Phosphorus forms insoluble complexes with Ca and Mg in alkaline soils and with Al and Fe in acidic soils that make the phosphorus unavailable for plant roots.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] It has been shown that PHR1, a MYB-related transcription factor, is a master regulator of P-starvation response in plants.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Drought stress, defined as naturally occurring water deficit, is a main cause of crop losses in agriculture.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] This is because water is essential for many fundamental processes in plant growth.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] It has become especially important in recent years to find a way to combat drought stress.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] A decrease in precipitation and consequent increase in drought are extremely likely in the future due to an increase in global warming.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Plants have come up with many mechanisms and adaptations to try and deal with drought stress.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] One of the leading ways that plants combat drought stress is by closing their stomata.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] A key hormone regulating stomatal opening and closing is abscisic acid (ABA).
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Synthesis of ABA causes the ABA to bind to receptors.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] This binding then affects the opening of ion channels, thereby decreasing turgor pressure in the stomata and causing them to close.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Recent studies by Gonzalez-Villagra, et al., have shown how ABA levels increased in drought-stressed plants (2018).
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] They showed that when plants were placed in a stressful situation, they produced more ABA to try to conserve any water they had in their leaves.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Another extremely important factor in dealing with drought stress and regulating the uptake and export of water is aquaporins (AQPs).
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] AQPs are integral membrane proteins that make up channels.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] These channels' main job is the transport of water and other essential solutes.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] AQPs are both transcriptionally and post-transcriptionally regulated by many different factors such as ABA, GA3, pH and Ca2+; and the specific levels of AQPs in certain parts of the plant, such as roots or leaves, helps to draw as much water into the plant as possible.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] By understanding the mechanisms of both AQPs and the hormone ABA, scientists will be better able to produce drought-resistant plants in the future.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] A study by Tombesi et al., found that plants which had previously been exposed to drought were able to minimize water loss and decrease water use.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] They found that plants which were exposed to drought conditions actually changed the way they regulated their stomata and what they called "hydraulic safety margin" so as to decrease the vulnerability of the plant.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] By changing the regulation of stomata and subsequently the transpiration, plants were able to function better when less water was available.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] For animals, the most stressful of all the abiotic stressors is heat.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] This is because many species are unable to regulate their internal body temperature.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Even in the species that are able to regulate their own temperature, it is not always a completely accurate system.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Temperature determines metabolic rates, heart rates, and other very important factors within the bodies of animals, so an extreme temperature change can easily distress the animal's body.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Animals can respond to extreme heat, for example, through natural heat acclimation or by burrowing into the ground to find a cooler space.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] It is also possible to see in animals that a high genetic diversity is beneficial in providing resiliency against harsh abiotic stressors.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] This acts as a sort of stock room when a species is plagued by the perils of natural selection.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] A variety of galling insects are among the most specialized and diverse herbivores on the planet, and their extensive protections against abiotic stress factors have helped the insect in gaining that position of honor.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Biodiversity is determined by many things, and one of them is abiotic stress.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] If an environment is highly stressful, biodiversity tends to be low.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] If abiotic stress does not have a strong presence in an area, the biodiversity will be much higher.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] This idea leads into the understanding of how abiotic stress and endangered species are related.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] It has been observed through a variety of environments that as the level of abiotic stress increases, the number of species decreases.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] This means that species are more likely to become population threatened, endangered, and even extinct, when and where abiotic stress is especially harsh.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Data suggests that anthropogenic activity has increased the global temperature, and likely increased the odds of extreme climate events such as drought, fire conditions and flooding.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] Threats to organisms and ecosystem biodiversity due to increased abiotic stress are one major impact of this change.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] The effects of climate change on biomes vary due to the location, patterns of precipitation, and the organisms which inhabit them.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] On the species level, the increased abiotic stress due to climate change can lead to adaptations which increase a species' reproductive success under these conditions.
[src:autotroph/abiotic-stress] However, such highly specialized adaptations may leave species vulnerable to other stresses.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] In ecology, **local abundance** is the relative representation of a species in a particular ecosystem.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] It is usually measured as the number of individuals found per sample.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] The ratio of abundance of one species to one or multiple other species living in an ecosystem is referred to as relative species abundances.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] Both indicators are relevant for computing biodiversity.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] A variety of sampling methods are used to measure abundance.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] For larger animals, these may include spotlight counts, track counts and roadkill counts, as well as presence at monitoring stations.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] In many plant communities the abundances of plant species are measured by plant cover, i.e. the relative area covered by different plant species in a small plot.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] Abundance is in simplest terms usually measured by identifying and counting every individual of every species in a given sector.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] It is common for the distribution of species to be skewed so that a few species take up the bulk of individuals collected.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] Relative species abundance is calculated by dividing the number of species from one group by the total number of species from all groups.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] These measures are all a part of community ecology.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] Understanding patterns within a community is easy when the community has a relatively low number of species.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] However most communities do not have a low number of species.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] Measuring species abundance allows for understanding of how species are distributed within an ecosystem.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] For example, salt water marshes have an influx of sea water, causing only a few species which are adapted to be able to survive in both salt and fresh water to be abundant.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] Inversely in land locked wetlands, the species abundance is more evenly distributed among the species who live within the wetland.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] In most ecosystems in which abundance has been calculated, most often only a small number of species are abundant, while a large number are pretty rare.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] These abundant species are often generalists, with many rare species being specialists.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] High density of a species in multiple localities will usually lead to it being relatively abundant over all in an ecosystem.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] Therefore, high local abundance can be directly linked to high regional distribution.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] Species with high abundance are likely to have more offspring, and these offspring in turn are more likely to colonize a new sector of the ecosystem than a species which is less abundant.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] Thus begins a positive feedback loop leading to a species distribution in which a few "core species" are wide spread, and the other species are restricted and scarce known as satellite species.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] Species abundance distribution (SAD) is one of the main uses of this measurement.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] SAD is a measurement of how common, or rare species are within an ecosystem.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] This allows researchers to assess how different species are distributed throughout an ecosystem.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] SAD is one of the most basic measurements in ecology and is used very often, therefore many different methods of measurement and analysis have developed.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] There are several methods for measuring abundance.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] An example of this is Semi-Quantitive Abundance ratings.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] These are measurement methods which involve estimation based on viewing a specific area of a designated size.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] The two Semi-Quantitive Abundance ratings used are known as the D.A.F.O.R, and the A.C.F.O.R.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] These methods are useful for getting a rough estimate of the species abundance in a designated area (quadrant), but they are not exact or objective measurements.
[src:autotroph/abundance-ecology] Therefore, if another method of measuring abundance is available, it should be used, as this will lead to more useful and quantifiable data.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] When consumed in a metabolic process, ATP converts either to adenosine diphosphate (ADP) or to adenosine monophosphate (AMP).
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Other processes, such as oxidative phosphorylation or substrate-level phosphorylation, regenerate ATP.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is also a precursor to DNA and RNA, and is used as a coenzyme.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Daily, an average adult human recycles through synthesis and hydrolysis around 50 kilograms of ATP (about 100 moles).
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] From the perspective of biochemistry, ATP is classified as a nucleoside triphosphate, which indicates that it consists of three components: a nitrogenous base (adenine), the sugar ribose, and the triphosphate.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP consists of three parts: a sugar, an amine base, and a phosphate group.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] More specifically, ATP consists of an adenine attached by the #9-nitrogen atom to the 1′ carbon atom of a sugar (ribose), which in turn is attached at the 5' carbon atom of the sugar to a triphosphate group.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] In its many reactions related to metabolism, the adenine and sugar groups remain unchanged, but the triphosphate is converted to di- and monophosphate, giving respectively the derivatives ADP and AMP.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The three phosphoryl groups are labeled as alpha (α), beta (β), and, for the terminal phosphate, gamma (γ).
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] In neutral solution, ionized ATP exists mostly as ATP4−, with a small proportion of ATP3−.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Polyanionic and featuring a potentially chelating polyphosphate group, ATP binds metal cations with high affinity.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The binding constant for Mg2+ is (9554).
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The binding of a divalent cation, almost always magnesium, strongly affects the interaction of ATP with various proteins.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Due to the strength of the ATP-Mg2+ interaction, ATP exists in the cell mostly as a complex with Mg2+ bonded to the phosphate oxygen centers.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] A second magnesium ion is critical for ATP binding in the kinase domain.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The presence of Mg2+ regulates kinase activity.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] It is interesting from an RNA world perspective that ATP can carry a Mg2+ ion which catalyzes RNA polymerization.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Salts of ATP can be isolated as colorless solids.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is stable in aqueous solutions between pH 6.8 and 7.4 (in the absence of catalysts).
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] At more extreme pH levels, it rapidly hydrolyses to ADP and phosphate.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Living cells maintain the ratio of ATP to ADP at a point ten orders of magnitude from equilibrium, with ATP concentrations fivefold higher than the concentration of ADP.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] In the context of biochemical reactions, the P-O-P bonds are frequently referred to as *high-energy bonds*.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] releases Δ*G*°' = −30.5 kJ/mol (−7.3 kcal/mol) of Gibbs free energy under standard conditions when all metabolite concentrations are 1 mol/L.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] This may differ under physiological conditions if the reactant and products are not exactly in these ionization states.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] At cytoplasmic conditions, where the ADP/ATP ratio is 10 orders of magnitude from equilibrium, the Δ*G* is around −57 kJ/mol.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Along with pH, the free energy change of ATP hydrolysis is also associated with Mg2+ concentration, from ΔG°' = −35.7 kJ/mol at a Mg2+ concentration of zero, to ΔG°' = −31 kJ/mol at [Mg2+] = 5 mM.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Higher concentrations of Mg2+ decrease free energy released in the reaction due to binding of Mg2+ ions to negatively charged oxygen atoms of ATP at pH 7.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] A typical intracellular concentration of ATP is 1–10 μmol per gram of muscle tissue in a variety of eukaryotes.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The dephosphorylation of ATP and rephosphorylation of ADP and AMP occur repeatedly in the course of aerobic metabolism.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP can be produced by a number of distinct cellular processes; the three main pathways in eukaryotes are (1) glycolysis, (2) the citric acid cycle/oxidative phosphorylation, and (3) beta-oxidation.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The overall process of oxidizing glucose to carbon dioxide, the combination of pathways 1 and 2, known as cellular respiration, produces about 30 equivalents of ATP from each molecule of glucose.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP production by a non-photosynthetic aerobic eukaryote occurs mainly in the mitochondria, which comprise nearly 25% of the volume of a typical cell.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] In glycolysis, glucose and glycerol are metabolized to pyruvate.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis generates two equivalents of ATP through substrate phosphorylation catalyzed by two enzymes, phosphoglycerate kinase (PGK) and pyruvate kinase.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Two equivalents of nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NADH) are also produced, which can be oxidized via the electron transport chain and result in the generation of additional ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The pyruvate generated as an end-product of glycolysis is a substrate for the citric acid cycle.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis is viewed as consisting of two phases with five steps each.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] In phase 1, "the preparatory phase", glucose is converted to 2 d-glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate (g3p).
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] One ATP is invested in Step 1, and another ATP is invested in Step 3.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Steps 1 and 3 of glycolysis are referred to as "Priming Steps".
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] In Phase 2, two equivalents of g3p are converted to two pyruvates.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Also, in Step 10, two further equivalents of ATP are produced.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] In Steps 7 and 10, ATP is generated from ADP.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] A net of two ATPs is formed in the glycolysis cycle.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The glycolysis pathway is later associated with the Citric Acid Cycle, which produces additional equivalents of ATP.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis is regulated allosterically by a number of metabolic compounds.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] For example, hexokinase is directly inhibited by its product, glucose-6-phosphate, and pyruvate kinase is inhibited by ATP itself.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The main control point for the glycolytic pathway is phosphofructokinase 1 (PFK1), which is allosterically inhibited by high concentrations of ATP and activated by high concentrations of AMP.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The inhibition of PFK1 by ATP is unusual since ATP is also a substrate in the reaction catalyzed by PFK1.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The active form of PFK1 enzyme is a tetramer that exists in two conformations, only one of which binds the second substrate fructose-6-phosphate (F6P).
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The PFK1 enzyme has two binding sites for ATP – the active site is accessible in either protein conformation, but ATP binding to the inhibitor site stabilizes the conformation that binds F6P poorly.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] A number of other small molecules can compensate for the ATP-induced shift in equilibrium conformation and reactivate PFK1, including cyclic AMP, ammonium ions, inorganic phosphate, fructose 1,6-bisphosphate and fructose 2,6-bisphosphate.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] In the mitochondrion, pyruvate is oxidized by the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex to the acetyl group, which is fully oxidized to carbon dioxide by the citric acid cycle.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] NADH and FADH2 are recycled (to NAD+ and FAD, respectively) by oxidative phosphorylation, generating additional ATP.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The oxidation of NADH results in the synthesis of 2–3 equivalents of ATP, and the oxidation of one FADH2 yields between 1–2 equivalents of ATP.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The majority of cellular ATP is generated by this process.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Although the citric acid cycle itself does not involve molecular oxygen, it is an obligately aerobic process because O2 is used to recycle the NADH and FADH2.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] In the absence of oxygen, the citric acid cycle ceases.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The generation of ATP by the mitochondrion from cytosolic NADH relies on the malate-aspartate shuttle (and to a lesser extent, the glycerol-phosphate shuttle) because the inner mitochondrial membrane is impermeable to NADH and NAD+.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Instead of transferring the generated NADH, a malate dehydrogenase enzyme converts oxaloacetate to malate, which is translocated to the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Another malate dehydrogenase-catalyzed reaction occurs in the opposite direction, producing oxaloacetate and NADH from the newly transported malate and the mitochondrion's interior store of NAD+.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] A transaminase converts the oxaloacetate to aspartate for transport back across the membrane and into the intermembrane space.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] In oxidative phosphorylation, the passage of electrons from NADH and FADH2 through the electron transport chain releases the energy to pump protons out of the mitochondrial matrix and into the intermembrane space.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] This pumping generates a proton motive force that is the net effect of a pH gradient and an electric potential gradient across the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Flow of protons down this potential gradient – that is, from the intermembrane space to the matrix – yields ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Most of the ATP synthesized in the mitochondria will be used for cellular processes in the cytosol; thus it must be exported from its site of synthesis in the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP outward movement is favored by the inner mitochondrial membrane's electrochemical potential because the cytosol has a relatively positive charge compared to the relatively negative matrix.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] For every ATP transported out, it costs 1 H+.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Therefore, making and exporting one ATP requires 4H+.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The inner membrane contains an antiporter, the ADP/ATP translocase, which is an integral membrane protein used to exchange newly synthesized ATP in the matrix for ADP in the intermembrane space.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The citric acid cycle is regulated mainly by the availability of key substrates, particularly the ratio of NAD+ to NADH and the concentrations of calcium, inorganic phosphate, ATP, ADP, and AMP.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Citrate – the ion that gives its name to the cycle – is a feedback inhibitor of citrate synthase and also inhibits PFK, providing a direct link between the regulation of the citric acid cycle and glycolysis.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] In the presence of air and various cofactors and enzymes, fatty acids are converted to acetyl-CoA.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Each cycle of beta-oxidation shortens the fatty acid chain by two carbon atoms and produces one equivalent each of acetyl-CoA, NADH, and FADH2.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The acetyl-CoA is metabolized by the citric acid cycle to generate ATP, while the NADH and FADH2 are used by oxidative phosphorylation to generate ATP.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Dozens of ATP equivalents are generated by the beta-oxidation of a single long acyl chain.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] In oxidative phosphorylation, the key control point is the reaction catalyzed by cytochrome c oxidase, which is regulated by the availability of its substrate – the reduced form of cytochrome c.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Thus, a high ratio of [NADH] to [NAD+] or a high ratio of [ADP] [Pi] to [ATP] imply a high amount of reduced cytochrome c and a high level of cytochrome c oxidase activity.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] An additional level of regulation is introduced by the transport rates of ATP and NADH between the mitochondrial matrix and the cytoplasm.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies can be used as fuels, yielding 22 ATP and 2 GTP molecules per acetoacetate molecule when oxidized in the mitochondria.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies are transported from the liver to other tissues, where acetoacetate and *beta*-hydroxybutyrate can be reconverted to acetyl-CoA to produce reducing equivalents (NADH and FADH2), via the citric acid cycle.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies cannot be used as fuel by the liver, because the liver lacks the enzyme β-ketoacyl-CoA transferase, also called thiolase.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetoacetate in low concentrations is taken up by the liver and undergoes detoxification through the methylglyoxal pathway which ends with lactate.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetoacetate in high concentrations is absorbed by cells other than those in the liver and enters a different pathway via 1,2-propanediol.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Though the pathway follows a different series of steps requiring ATP, 1,2-propanediol can be turned into pyruvate.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Fermentation is the metabolism of organic compounds in the absence of air.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] It involves substrate-level phosphorylation in the absence of a respiratory electron transport chain.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Anaerobic respiration is respiration in the absence of O2.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Prokaryotes can utilize a variety of electron acceptors.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] These include nitrate, sulfate, and carbon dioxide.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] In anaerobic organisms and prokaryotes, different pathways result in ATP.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is produced in the chloroplasts of green plants in a process similar to oxidative phosphorylation, called photophosphorylation.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP can also be synthesized through several so-called "replenishment" reactions catalyzed by the enzyme families of nucleoside diphosphate kinases (NDKs), which use other nucleoside triphosphates as a high-energy phosphate donor, and the ATP:guanido-phosphotransferase family.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] In plants, ATP is synthesized in the thylakoid membrane of the chloroplast.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The process is called photophosphorylation.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The "machinery" is similar to that in mitochondria except that light energy is used to pump protons across a membrane to produce a proton-motive force.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP synthase then ensues exactly as in oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Some of the ATP produced in the chloroplasts is consumed in the Calvin cycle, which produces triose sugars.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The total quantity of ATP in the human body is about 0.1 mol/L.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The majority of ATP is recycled from ADP by the aforementioned processes.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Thus, at any given time, the total amount of ATP + ADP remains fairly constant.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The energy used by human cells in an adult requires the hydrolysis of 100 to 150 mol/L of ATP daily, which means a human will typically use their body weight worth of ATP over the course of the day.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Each equivalent of ATP is recycled 1000–1500 times during a single day (150 / 0.1 = 1500), at approximately 9×1020 molecules/s.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The conversion of ATP to ADP is the principal mechanism for energy supply in biological processes.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] However, removing a phosphate group from ADP to produce adenosine monophosphate (AMP) also produces extra energy.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is involved in signal transduction by serving as substrate for kinases, enzymes that transfer phosphate groups.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Kinases are the most common ATP-binding proteins.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] They share a small number of common folds.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Phosphorylation of a protein by a kinase can activate a cascade such as the mitogen-activated protein kinase cascade.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is also a substrate of adenylate cyclase, most commonly in G protein-coupled receptor signal transduction pathways and is transformed to second messenger, cyclic AMP, which is involved in triggering calcium signals by the release of calcium from intracellular stores.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] This form of signal transduction is particularly important in brain function, although it is involved in the regulation of a multitude of other cellular processes.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is one of four monomers required in the synthesis of RNA.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The process is promoted by RNA polymerases.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] A similar process occurs in the formation of DNA, except that ATP is first converted to the deoxyribonucleotide dATP.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Like many condensation reactions in nature, DNA replication and DNA transcription also consume ATP.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase enzymes consume ATP in the attachment tRNA to amino acids, forming aminoacyl-tRNA complexes.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Aminoacyl transferase binds AMP-amino acid to tRNA.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The amino acid is coupled to the penultimate nucleotide at the 3′-end of the tRNA (the A in the sequence CCA) via an ester bond (roll over in illustration).
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Transporting chemicals out of a cell against a gradient is often associated with ATP hydrolysis.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Transport is mediated by ATP binding cassette transporters.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The human genome encodes 48 ABC transporters, that are used for exporting drugs, lipids, and other compounds.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Cells secrete ATP to communicate with other cells in a process called purinergic signalling.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP serves as a neurotransmitter in many parts of the nervous system, modulates ciliary beating, affects vascular oxygen supply etc.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is either secreted directly across the cell membrane through channel proteins or is pumped into vesicles which then fuse with the membrane.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Cells detect ATP using the purinergic receptor proteins P2X and P2Y.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP has been shown to be a critically important signalling molecule for microglia - neuron interactions in the adult brain, as well as during brain development.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Furthermore, tissue-injury induced ATP-signalling is a major factor in rapid microglial phenotype changes.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Muscle contractions are regulated by signaling pathways, although different muscle types being regulated by specific pathways and stimuli based on their particular function.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] However, in all muscle types, contraction is performed by the proteins actin and myosin.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] When ATPase hydrolyzes the bound ATP into ADP and inorganic phosphate, myosin is positioned in a way that it can bind to actin.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Myosin bound by ADP and Pi forms cross-bridges with actin and the subsequent release of ADP and Pi releases energy as the power stroke.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The power stroke causes actin filament to slide past the myosin filament, shortening the muscle and causing a contraction.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Another ATP molecule can then bind to myosin, releasing it from actin and allowing this process to repeat.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP has recently been proposed to act as a biological hydrotrope and has been shown to affect proteome-wide solubility.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetyl phosphate (AcP), a precursor to ATP, can readily be synthesized at modest yields from thioacetate in pH 7 and 20 °C and pH 8 and 50 °C, although acetyl phosphate is less stable in warmer temperatures and alkaline conditions than in cooler and acidic to neutral conditions.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] It is unable to promote polymerization of ribonucleotides and amino acids and was only capable of phosphorylation of organic compounds.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] It was shown that it can promote aggregation and stabilization of AMP in the presence of Na+, aggregation of nucleotides could promote polymerization above 75 °C in the absence of Na+.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] It is possible that polymerization promoted by AcP could occur at mineral surfaces.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] It was shown that ADP can only be phosphorylated to ATP by AcP and other nucleoside triphosphates were not phosphorylated by AcP.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] This might explain why all lifeforms use ATP to drive biochemical reactions.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Biochemistry laboratories often use *in vitro* studies to explore ATP-dependent molecular processes.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP analogs are also used in X-ray crystallography to determine a protein structure in complex with ATP, often together with other substrates.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Enzyme inhibitors of ATP-dependent enzymes such as kinases are needed to examine the binding sites and transition states involved in ATP-dependent reactions.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Most useful ATP analogs cannot be hydrolyzed as ATP would be; instead, they trap the enzyme in a structure closely related to the ATP-bound state.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Adenosine 5′-(γ-thiotriphosphate) is an extremely common ATP analog in which one of the gamma-phosphate oxygens is replaced by a sulfur atom; this anion is hydrolyzed at a dramatically slower rate than ATP itself and functions as an inhibitor of ATP-dependent processes.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] In crystallographic studies, hydrolysis transition states are modeled by the bound vanadate ion.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Caution is warranted in interpreting the results of experiments using ATP analogs, since some enzymes can hydrolyze them at appreciable rates at high concentration.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is used intravenously for some heart-related conditions.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP was discovered in 1929 from muscle tissue by Karl Lohmann and Jendrassik and, independently, by Cyrus Fiske and Yellapragada Subba Rao of Harvard Medical School, both teams competing against each other to find an assay for phosphorus.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] It was proposed to be the intermediary between energy-yielding and energy-requiring reactions in cells by Fritz Albert Lipmann in 1941.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] He played a major role in establishing that ATP is the energy currency of a cell.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] It was first synthesized in the laboratory by Alexander Todd in 1948, and he was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1957 partly for this work.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The 1978 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to Peter Dennis Mitchell for the discovery of the chemiosmotic mechanism of ATP synthesis.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] The 1997 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was divided, one half jointly to Paul D.
[src:autotroph/adenosine-triphosphate] Walker "for their elucidation of the enzymatic mechanism underlying the synthesis of adenosine triphosphate (ATP)" and the other half to Jens C.
[src:autotroph/albert-bernhard-frank] Frank was commissioned to develop practical methods for truffle cultivation by the King of Prussia (Wilhelm I).
[src:autotroph/albert-bernhard-frank] Although this project was not successful, it led to his elucidation of the nature and development of mycorrhizae.
[src:autotroph/albert-bernhard-frank] The history and impacts of Frank's work on mycorrhizae were reviewed by Trappe.
[src:autotroph/albert-bernhard-frank] The bacterial genus *Frankia* and family *Frankiaceae* were named after him.
[src:autotroph/albert-bernhard-frank] In 1877, Albert Frank coined the term "symbiosis" (German: *Symbiose*) to describe the nature of lichens.
[src:autotroph/albert-bernhard-frank] The standard author abbreviation A.B.Frank is used to indicate this person as the author when citing a botanical name.
[src:autotroph/algae] Algae are polyphyletic as they have multiple evolutionary origins.
[src:autotroph/algae] Although algae with two-membraned chloroplasts seem to form a paraphyletic group within the clade Archaeplastida, other algae with chloroplasts that have three or more membranes evolved from protists that acquired photosynthesis after engulfing archaeplastids.
[src:autotroph/algae] Most algae are single-celled organisms without roots, leaves, or stems.
[src:autotroph/algae] Most are photoautotrophs and the main primary producers of aquatic ecosystems, although some are mixotrophs that derive metabolic energy both from internal photosynthesis and from foraging external nutrients.
[src:autotroph/algae] Some unicellular algae have become heterotrophs or parasites, relying entirely on external energy sources.
[src:autotroph/algae] Algae have photosynthetic machinery ultimately derived from cyanobacteria that produce oxygen by splitting water molecules, unlike photosynthetic bacteria.
[src:autotroph/algae] Fossilized filamentous algae from the Vindhya basin have been dated to 1.6 to 1.7 billion years ago.
[src:autotroph/algae] Because of the wide range of types of algae, there is a correspondingly wide range of industrial and traditional applications in human society.
[src:autotroph/algae] Traditional seaweed farming practices have existed for thousands of years and have strong traditions in East Asian food cultures.
[src:autotroph/algae] More modern algaculture applications extend the food traditions for other applications, including cattle feed, using algae for bioremediation or pollution control, transforming sunlight into algae fuels or other chemicals used in industrial processes, and in medical and scientific applications.
[src:autotroph/algae] The singular *alga* is the Latin word for "seaweed" and retains that meaning in English.
[src:autotroph/algae] Although some speculate that it is related to Latin *algēre*, "be cold", no reason is known to associate seaweed with temperature.
[src:autotroph/algae] A more likely source is *alliga*, "binding, entwining".
[src:autotroph/algae] The Ancient Greek word for "seaweed" was φῦκος (*phŷkos*), which could mean either the seaweed (probably red algae) or a red dye derived from it.
[src:autotroph/algae] The Latinization, *fūcus*, meant primarily the cosmetic rouge.
[src:autotroph/algae] The etymology is uncertain, but a strong candidate has long been some word related to the Biblical פוך (*pūk*), "paint" (if not that word itself), a cosmetic eye-shadow used by the Ancient Egyptians and other inhabitants of the eastern Mediterranean.
[src:autotroph/algae] It could be any color: black, red, green, or blue.
[src:autotroph/algae] The study of algae is most commonly called phycology (from Greek *phykos* 'seaweed'); the term algology is falling out of use.
[src:autotroph/algae] The algae are a heterogeneous group of mostly photosynthetic organisms that produce oxygen and lack the reproductive features and structural complexity of land plants.
[src:autotroph/algae] This concept includes the cyanobacteria, which are prokaryotes, and all photosynthetic protists, which are eukaryotes.
[src:autotroph/algae] They contain chlorophyll *a* as their primary photosynthetic pigment, and generally inhabit aquatic environments.
[src:autotroph/algae] However, there are many exceptions to this definition.
[src:autotroph/algae] Many non-photosynthetic protists are included in the study of algae, such as the heterotrophic relatives of euglenophytes or the numerous species of colorless algae that have lost their chlorophyll during evolution (e.g., *Prototheca*).
[src:autotroph/algae] Some exceptional species of algae tolerate dry terrestrial habitats, such as soil, rocks, or caves hidden from light sources, although they still need enough moisture to become active.
[src:autotroph/algae] A range of algal morphologies is exhibited, and convergence of features in unrelated groups is common.
[src:autotroph/algae] The only groups to exhibit three-dimensional multicellular thalli are the reds and browns, and some chlorophytes.
[src:autotroph/algae] Apical growth is constrained to subsets of these groups: the florideophyte reds, various browns, and the charophytes.
[src:autotroph/algae] The form of charophytes is quite different from those of reds and browns, because they have distinct nodes, separated by internode 'stems'; whorls of branches reminiscent of the horsetails occur at the nodes.
[src:autotroph/algae] Conceptacles are another polyphyletic trait; they appear in the coralline algae and the Hildenbrandiales, as well as the browns.
[src:autotroph/algae] Most of the simpler algae are unicellular flagellates or amoeboids, but colonial and nonmotile forms have developed independently among several of the groups.
[src:autotroph/algae] In three lines, even higher levels of organization have been reached, with full tissue differentiation.
[src:autotroph/algae] These are the brown algae,—some of which may reach 50 m in length (kelps)—the red algae, and the green algae.
[src:autotroph/algae] The most complex forms are found among the charophyte algae (see Charales and Charophyta), in a lineage that eventually led to the higher land plants.
[src:autotroph/algae] The innovation that defines these nonalgal plants is the presence of female reproductive organs with protective cell layers that protect the zygote and developing embryo.
[src:autotroph/algae] Hence, the land plants are referred to as the Embryophytes.
[src:autotroph/algae] The term algal turf is commonly used but poorly defined.
[src:autotroph/algae] Algal turfs are thick, carpet-like beds of seaweed that retain sediment and compete with foundation species like corals and kelps, and they are usually less than 15 cm tall.
[src:autotroph/algae] Such a turf may consist of one or more species, and will generally cover an area in the order of a square metre or more.
[src:autotroph/algae] Many algae, particularly species of the Characeae, have served as model experimental organisms to understand the mechanisms of the water permeability of membranes, osmoregulation, salt tolerance, cytoplasmic streaming, and the generation of action potentials.
[src:autotroph/algae] Plant hormones are found not only in higher plants, but in algae, too.
[src:autotroph/algae] Rhodophyta, Chlorophyta, and Heterokontophyta, the three main algal divisions, have life cycles which show considerable variation and complexity.
[src:autotroph/algae] In general, an asexual phase exists where the seaweed's cells are diploid, a sexual phase where the cells are haploid, followed by fusion of the male and female gametes.
[src:autotroph/algae] Asexual reproduction permits efficient population increases, but less variation is possible.
[src:autotroph/algae] Commonly, in sexual reproduction of unicellular and colonial algae, two specialized, sexually compatible, haploid gametes make physical contact and fuse to form a zygote.
[src:autotroph/algae] To ensure a successful mating, the development and release of gametes is highly synchronized and regulated; pheromones may play a key role in these processes.
[src:autotroph/algae] Sexual reproduction allows for more variation and provides the benefit of efficient recombinational repair of DNA damage during meiosis, a key stage of the sexual cycle.
[src:autotroph/algae] However, sexual reproduction is more costly than asexual reproduction.
[src:autotroph/algae] Meiosis has been shown to occur in many different species of algae.
[src:autotroph/algae] Linnaeus, in *Species Plantarum* (1753), the starting point for modern botanical nomenclature, recognized 14 genera of algae, of which only four are currently considered among algae.
[src:autotroph/algae] In *Systema Naturae*, Linnaeus described the genera *Volvox* and *Corallina*, and a species of *Acetabularia* (as *Madrepora*), among the animals.
[src:autotroph/algae] In 1768, Samuel Gottlieb Gmelin (1744–1774) published the *Historia Fucorum*, the first work dedicated to marine algae and the first book on marine biology to use the then new binomial nomenclature of Linnaeus.
[src:autotroph/algae] It included elaborate illustrations of seaweed and marine algae on folded leaves.
[src:autotroph/algae] Harvey (1811–1866) and Lamouroux (1813) were the first to divide macroscopic algae into four divisions based on their pigmentation.
[src:autotroph/algae] This is the first use of a biochemical criterion in plant systematics.
[src:autotroph/algae] Harvey's four divisions are: red algae (Rhodospermae), brown algae (Melanospermae), green algae (Chlorospermae), and Diatomaceae.
[src:autotroph/algae] At this time, microscopic algae were discovered and reported by a different group of workers (e.g., O.
[src:autotroph/algae] Müller and Ehrenberg) studying the Infusoria (microscopic organisms).
[src:autotroph/algae] Unlike macroalgae, which were clearly viewed as plants, microalgae were frequently considered animals because they are often motile.
[src:autotroph/algae] Even the nonmotile (coccoid) microalgae were sometimes merely seen as stages of the lifecycle of plants, macroalgae, or animals.
[src:autotroph/algae] Although used as a taxonomic category in some pre-Darwinian classifications, e.g., Linnaeus (1753), de Jussieu (1789), Lamouroux (1813), Harvey (1836), Horaninow (1843), Agassiz (1859), Wilson & Cassin (1864), in further classifications, the "algae" are seen as an artificial, polyphyletic group.
[src:autotroph/algae] Throughout the 20th century, most classifications treated the following groups as divisions or classes of algae: cyanophytes, rhodophytes, chrysophytes, xanthophytes, bacillariophytes, phaeophytes, pyrrhophytes (cryptophytes and dinophytes), euglenophytes, and chlorophytes.
[src:autotroph/algae] With the abandonment of plant-animal dichotomous classification, most groups of algae (sometimes all) were included in Protista, later also abandoned in favour of Eukaryota.
[src:autotroph/algae] However, as a legacy of the older plant life scheme, some groups that were also treated as protozoans in the past still have duplicated classifications (see ambiregnal protists).
[src:autotroph/algae] In other cases, some groups were originally characterized as parasitic algae (e.g., *Chlorochytrium*), but later were seen as endophytic algae.
[src:autotroph/algae] Some filamentous bacteria (e.g., *Beggiatoa*) were originally seen as algae.
[src:autotroph/algae] Furthermore, groups like the apicomplexans are also parasites derived from ancestors that possessed plastids, but are not included in any group traditionally seen as algae.
[src:autotroph/algae] The most recent estimate (as of January 2024) documents 50,605 living and 10,556 fossil algal species, according to the online database AlgaeBase.
[src:autotroph/algae] They are classified into 15 phyla or divisions.
[src:autotroph/algae] Some phyla are not photosynthetic, namely Picophyta and Rhodelphidophyta, but they are included in the database due to their close relationship with red algae.
[src:autotroph/algae] The various algal phyla can be differentiated according to several biological traits.
[src:autotroph/algae] They have distinct morphologies, photosynthetic pigmentation, storage products, cell wall composition, and mechanisms of carbon concentration.
[src:autotroph/algae] Some phyla have unique cellular structures.
[src:autotroph/algae] , the most common genus of cyanobacteria.
[src:autotroph/algae] Among prokaryotes, five major groups of bacteria have evolved the ability to photosynthesize, including heliobacteria, green sulfur and nonsulfur bacteria and proteobacteria.
[src:autotroph/algae] However, the only lineage where oxygenic photosynthesis has evolved is in the cyanobacteria, often known as blue-green algae for their blue-green (cyan) coloration.
[src:autotroph/algae] They are classified as the phylum Cyanobacteriota or Cyanophyta.
[src:autotroph/algae] However, this phylum also includes two classes of non-photosynthetic bacteria: Melainabacteria (also called Vampirovibrionia or Vampirovibrionophyceae) and Sericytochromatia (also known as Blackallbacteria).
[src:autotroph/algae] A third class contains the photosynthetic ones, known as Cyanophyceae (also called Cyanobacteriia or Oxyphotobacteria).
[src:autotroph/algae] As bacteria, their cells lack membrane-bound organelles, with the exception of thylakoids.
[src:autotroph/algae] Like other algae, cyanobacteria have chlorophyll *a* as their primary photosynthetic pigment.
[src:autotroph/algae] Their accessory pigments include phycobilins (phycoerythrobilin and phycocyanobilin), carotenoids and, in some cases, *b*, *d*, or *f* chlorophylls, generally distributed in phycobilisomes found in the surface of thylakoids.
[src:autotroph/algae] They display a variety of body forms, such as single cells, colonies, and unbranched or branched filaments.
[src:autotroph/algae] Their cells are commonly covered in a sheath of mucilage, and they also have a typical gram-negative bacterial cell wall composed largely of peptidoglycan.
[src:autotroph/algae] They have various storage particles, including cyanophycin as aminoacid and nitrogen reserves, "cyanophycean starch" (similar to plant amylose) for carbohydrates, and lipid droplets.
[src:autotroph/algae] Their Rubisco enzymes are concentrated in carboxysomes.
[src:autotroph/algae] They occupy a diverse array of aquatic and terrestrial habitats, including extreme environments from hot springs to polar glaciers.
[src:autotroph/algae] Some are subterranean, living via hydrogen-based lithoautotrophy instead of photosynthesis.
[src:autotroph/algae] Three lineages of cyanobacteria, *Prochloraceae*, *Prochlorothrix* and *Prochlorococcus*, independently evolved to have chlorophylls *a* and *b* instead of phycobilisomes.
[src:autotroph/algae] Due to their different pigmentation, they were historically grouped in a separate division, Prochlorophyta, as this is the typical pigmentation seen in green algae (e.g., chlorophytes).
[src:autotroph/algae] Eventually, this classification became obsolete, as it is a polyphyletic grouping.
[src:autotroph/algae] Cyanobacteria are included as algae by most phycological sources and by the International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants, although a few authors exclude them from the definition of algae and reserve the term for eukaryotes only.
[src:autotroph/algae] Eukaryotic algae contain chloroplasts that are similar in structure to cyanobacteria.
[src:autotroph/algae] Chloroplasts contain circular DNA like that in cyanobacteria and are interpreted as representing reduced endosymbiotic cyanobacteria.
[src:autotroph/algae] However, the exact origin of the chloroplasts is different among separate lineages of algae, reflecting their acquisition during different endosymbiotic events.
[src:autotroph/algae] Many groups contain some members that are no longer photosynthetic.
[src:autotroph/algae] Some retain plastids, but not chloroplasts, while others have lost plastids entirely.
[src:autotroph/algae] Primary algae are those with "primary chloroplasts", i.e. chloroplasts with two membranes, evolved through a single symbiogenetic event with an endosymbiont β-cyanobacterium as early as 1.6 Gya during the Mesoproterozoic.
[src:autotroph/algae] These algae are mainly grouped in the clade Archaeplastida (meaning "ancient plastid"), which includes the major groups Viridiplantae (green algae *sensu lato* and all land plants) and Rhodophyta (red algae) as well as the minor group Glaucophyta (grey algae).
[src:autotroph/algae] Land plants (embryophytes) are pigmented similarly to green algae and likely evolved from the freshwater green algae clade Streptophyta, which is sister taxon to Chlorophyta (green algae *sensu stricto*) and the basal clade Prasinodermophyta.
[src:autotroph/algae] There is also a minor group of amoeboid protists with primary plastids evolved via different origin and at a much later date than archaeplastid chloroplasts.
[src:autotroph/algae] The four species of the euglyphid amoebae genus *Paulinella*, have cyanobionts (known as cyanelles) that perform photosynthesis, likely originated from the endosymbiosis of a α-cyanobacterium (probably an ancestral member of Chroococcales), about 90–140 Mya during the Cretaceous.
[src:autotroph/algae] Secondary algae are eukaryotes with "secondary chloroplasts", i.e. those evolved from phagocytosis and subsequent endosymbiosis of primary algae (mainly green or red algae) or other secondary algae, thus "stealing" the endosymbionts' photosynthetic capability.
[src:autotroph/algae] As a result, these algae have chloroplasts surrounded by three or more membranes, and appeared independently in various distantly related protist lineages.
[src:autotroph/algae] Two lineages of secondary algae, chlorarachniophytes and euglenophytes have "green" chloroplasts containing chlorophylls *a* and *b*.
[src:autotroph/algae] Their chloroplasts are surrounded by four and three membranes, respectively, and were probably retained from ingested green algae.
[src:autotroph/algae] Other groups have "red" chloroplasts containing chlorophylls *a* and *c*, and phycobilins.
[src:autotroph/algae] The shape can vary; they may be of discoid, plate-like, reticulate, cup-shaped, spiral, or ribbon shaped.
[src:autotroph/algae] They have one or more pyrenoids to preserve protein and starch.
[src:autotroph/algae] The latter chlorophyll type is not known from any prokaryotes or primary chloroplasts, but genetic similarities with red algae suggest a relationship there.
[src:autotroph/algae] The typical dinoflagellate chloroplast has three membranes, but considerable diversity exists in chloroplasts within the group, and a number of endosymbiotic events apparently occurred.
[src:autotroph/algae] The Apicomplexa, a group of closely related parasites, also have plastids called apicoplasts, which are not photosynthetic.
[src:autotroph/algae] The Chromerida are the closest relatives of apicomplexans, and some have retained their chloroplasts.
[src:autotroph/algae] The three alveolate groups evolved from a common myzozoan ancestor that obtained chloroplasts.
[src:autotroph/algae] The distribution of algal species has been fairly well studied since the founding of phytogeography in the mid-19th century.
[src:autotroph/algae] Algae spread mainly by the dispersal of spores analogously to the dispersal of cryptogamic plants by spores.
[src:autotroph/algae] Spores can be found in a variety of environments: fresh and marine waters, air, soil, and in or on other organisms.
[src:autotroph/algae] Whether a spore is to grow into an adult organism depends on the species and the environmental conditions where the spore lands.
[src:autotroph/algae] The spores of freshwater algae are dispersed mainly by running water and wind, as well as by living carriers.
[src:autotroph/algae] However, not all bodies of water can carry all species of algae, as the chemical composition of certain water bodies limits the algae that can survive within them.
[src:autotroph/algae] Marine spores are often spread by ocean currents.
[src:autotroph/algae] Ocean water presents many vastly different habitats based on temperature and nutrient availability, resulting in phytogeographic zones, regions, and provinces.
[src:autotroph/algae] To some degree, the distribution of algae is subject to floristic discontinuities caused by geographical features, such as Antarctica, long distances of ocean or general land masses.
[src:autotroph/algae] It is, therefore, possible to identify species occurring by locality, such as "Pacific algae" or "North Sea algae".
[src:autotroph/algae] When they occur out of their localities, hypothesizing a transport mechanism is usually possible, such as the hulls of ships.
[src:autotroph/algae] For example, *Ulva reticulata* and *U. fasciata* travelled from the mainland to Hawaii in this manner.
[src:autotroph/algae] Mapping is possible for select species only: "there are many valid examples of confined distribution patterns." For example, *Clathromorphum* is an arctic genus and is not mapped far south of there.
[src:autotroph/algae] For example, according to one standard textbook, in the British Isles, the *UK Biodiversity Steering Group Report* estimated there to be 20,000 algal species in the UK.
[src:autotroph/algae] Another checklist reports only about 5,000 species.
[src:autotroph/algae] and so on, but lacking any scientific basis or reliable sources, these numbers have no more credibility than the British ones mentioned above.
[src:autotroph/algae] Most estimates also omit microscopic algae, such as phytoplankton.
[src:autotroph/algae] Algae are prominent in bodies of water, common in terrestrial environments, and are found in unusual environments, such as on snow and ice.
[src:autotroph/algae] Seaweeds grow mostly in shallow marine waters, less than 100 m (330 ft) deep; however, some such as *Navicula pennata* have been recorded to a depth of 360 m (1,180 ft).
[src:autotroph/algae] A type of algae, *Ancylonema nordenskioeldii*, was found in Greenland in areas known as the 'Dark Zone', which caused an increase in the rate of melting ice sheet.
[src:autotroph/algae] The same algae was found in the Italian Alps, after pink ice appeared on parts of the Presena glacier.
[src:autotroph/algae] The various sorts of algae play significant roles in aquatic ecology.
[src:autotroph/algae] Microscopic forms that live suspended in the water column (phytoplankton) provide the food base for most marine food chains.
[src:autotroph/algae] In very high densities (algal blooms), these algae may discolor the water and outcompete, poison, or asphyxiate other life forms.
[src:autotroph/algae] Algae can be used as indicator organisms to monitor pollution in various aquatic systems.
[src:autotroph/algae] In many cases, algal metabolism is sensitive to various pollutants.
[src:autotroph/algae] Due to this, the species composition of algal populations may shift in the presence of chemical pollutants.
[src:autotroph/algae] To detect these changes, algae can be sampled from the environment and maintained in laboratories with relative ease.
[src:autotroph/algae] Some species of algae form symbiotic relationships with other organisms.
[src:autotroph/algae] In these symbioses, the algae supply photosynthates (organic substances) to the host organism providing protection to the algal cells.
[src:autotroph/algae] The host organism derives some or all of its energy requirements from the algae.
[src:autotroph/algae] Lichens are defined by the International Association for Lichenology to be "an association of a fungus and a photosynthetic symbiont resulting in a stable vegetative body having a specific structure".
[src:autotroph/algae] The fungi, or mycobionts, are mainly from the Ascomycota with a few from the Basidiomycota.
[src:autotroph/algae] In nature, they do not occur separate from lichens.
[src:autotroph/algae] It is unknown when they began to associate.
[src:autotroph/algae] One or more mycobiont associates with the same phycobiont species, from the green algae, except that alternatively, the mycobiont may associate with a species of cyanobacteria (hence "photobiont" is the more accurate term).
[src:autotroph/algae] A photobiont may be associated with many different mycobionts or may live independently; accordingly, lichens are named and classified as fungal species.
[src:autotroph/algae] The association is termed a morphogenesis because the lichen has a form and capabilities not possessed by the symbiont species alone (they can be experimentally isolated).
[src:autotroph/algae] The photobiont possibly triggers otherwise latent genes in the mycobiont.
[src:autotroph/algae] Trentepohlia is an example of a common green alga genus worldwide that can grow on its own or be lichenised.
[src:autotroph/algae] Lichen thus share some of the habitat and often similar appearance with specialized species of algae (*aerophytes*) growing on exposed surfaces such as tree trunks and rocks and sometimes discoloring them.
[src:autotroph/algae] Coral reefs are accumulated from the calcareous exoskeletons of marine invertebrates of the order Scleractinia (stony corals).
[src:autotroph/algae] These animals metabolize sugar and oxygen to obtain energy for their cell-building processes, including secretion of the exoskeleton, with water and carbon dioxide as byproducts.
[src:autotroph/algae] Dinoflagellates (algal protists) are often endosymbionts in the cells of the coral-forming marine invertebrates, where they accelerate host-cell metabolism by generating sugar and oxygen immediately available through photosynthesis using incident light and the carbon dioxide produced by the host.
[src:autotroph/algae] Reef-building stony corals (hermatypic corals) require endosymbiotic algae from the genus *Symbiodinium* to be in a healthy condition.
[src:autotroph/algae] The loss of *Symbiodinium* from the host is known as coral bleaching, a condition which leads to the deterioration of a reef.
[src:autotroph/algae] Endosymbiontic green algae live close to the surface of some sponges, for example, breadcrumb sponges (*Halichondria panicea*).
[src:autotroph/algae] The alga is thus protected from predators; the sponge is provided with oxygen and sugars which can account for 50 to 80% of sponge growth in some species.
[src:autotroph/algae] Prokaryotic algae, i.e., cyanobacteria, are the only group of organisms where oxygenic photosynthesis has evolved.
[src:autotroph/algae] The oldest undisputed fossil evidence of cyanobacteria is dated at 2100 million years ago, although stromatolites, associated with cyanobacterial biofilms, appear as early as 3500 million years ago in the fossil record.
[src:autotroph/algae] Eukaryotic algae are polyphyletic thus their origin cannot be traced back to a single hypothetical common ancestor.
[src:autotroph/algae] It is thought that they came into existence when photosynthetic coccoid cyanobacteria got phagocytized by a unicellular heterotrophic eukaryote (a protist), giving rise to double-membranous primary plastids.
[src:autotroph/algae] Such symbiogenic events (primary symbiogenesis) are believed to have occurred more than 1.5 billion years ago during the Calymmian period, early in Boring Billion, but it is difficult to track the key events because of so much time gap.
[src:autotroph/algae] This process of serial cell "capture" and "enslavement" explains the diversity of photosynthetic eukaryotes.
[src:autotroph/algae] The oldest undisputed fossil evidence of eukaryotic algae is *Bangiomorpha pubescens*, a red alga found in rocks around 1047 million years old.
[src:autotroph/algae] Recent genomic and phylogenomic approaches have significantly clarified plastid genome evolution, the horizontal movement of endosymbiont genes to the "host" nuclear genome, and plastid spread throughout the eukaryotic tree of life.
[src:autotroph/algae] It is accepted that both euglenophytes and chlorarachniophytes obtained their chloroplasts from chlorophytes that became endosymbionts.
[src:autotroph/algae] In particular, euglenophyte chloroplasts share the most resemblance with the genus *Pyramimonas*.
[src:autotroph/algae] However, there is still no clear order in which the secondary and tertiary endosymbioses occurred for the "chromist" lineages (ochrophytes, cryptophytes, haptophytes and myzozoans).
[src:autotroph/algae] Two main models have been proposed to explain the order, both of which agree that cryptophytes obtained their chloroplasts from red algae.
[src:autotroph/algae] One model, hypothesized in 2014 by John W.
[src:autotroph/algae] Stiller and coauthors, suggests that a cryptophyte became the plastid of ochrophytes, which in turn became the plastid of myzozoans and haptophytes.
[src:autotroph/algae] The other model, suggested by Andrzej Bodył and coauthors in 2009, describes that a cryptophyte became the plastid of both haptophytes and ochrophytes, and it is a haptophyte that became the plastid of myzozoans instead.
[src:autotroph/algae] These charophyte algae probably already developed filamentous thalli and holdfasts that superficially resembled plant stems and roots, and probably had an isomorphic alternation of generations.
[src:autotroph/algae] They perhaps evolved some 850 mya and might even be as early as 1 Gya during the late phase of the Boring Billion.
[src:autotroph/algae] Algaculture is a form of aquaculture involving the farming of species of algae.
[src:autotroph/algae] The majority of algae that are intentionally cultivated fall into the category of microalgae (also referred to as phytoplankton, microphytes, or planktonic algae).
[src:autotroph/algae] Global production of farmed aquatic plants, overwhelmingly dominated by seaweeds, grew in output volume from 13.5 million tonnes in 1995, to just over 30 million tonnes in 2016 and 37.8 million tonnes in 2022 and 40 million tonnes in 2024.
[src:autotroph/algae] This increase was the result of production expansions led by China, followed by Malaysia, the Philippines, the United Republic of Tanzania, and the Russian Federation.
[src:autotroph/algae] Cultured microalgae already contribute to a wide range of sectors in the emerging bioeconomy.
[src:autotroph/algae] Research suggests there are large potentials and benefits of algaculture for the development of a future healthy and sustainable food system.
[src:autotroph/algae] Seaweed farming or kelp farming is the practice of cultivating and harvesting seaweed.
[src:autotroph/algae] In its simplest form farmers gather from natural beds, while at the other extreme farmers fully control the crop's life cycle.
[src:autotroph/algae] The seven most cultivated taxa are *Eucheuma* spp., *Kappaphycus alvarezii*, *Gracilaria* spp., *Saccharina japonica*, *Undaria pinnatifida*, *Pyropia* spp., and *Sargassum fusiforme*.
[src:autotroph/algae] *Eucheuma* and *K. alvarezii* are attractive for carrageenan (a gelling agent); *Gracilaria* is farmed for agar; the rest are eaten after limited processing.
[src:autotroph/algae] Seaweeds are different from mangroves and seagrasses, as they are photosynthetic algal organisms and are non-flowering.
[src:autotroph/algae] The largest seaweed-producing countries as of 2022 are China (58.62%) and Indonesia (28.6%); followed by South Korea (5.09%) and the Philippines (4.19%).
[src:autotroph/algae] Seaweed farming has frequently been developed to improve economic conditions and to reduce fishing pressure.
[src:autotroph/algae] The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) reported that world production in 2019 was over 35 million tonnes.
[src:autotroph/algae] North America produced some 23,000 tonnes of wet seaweed.
[src:autotroph/algae] Alaska, Maine, France, and Norway each more than doubled their seaweed production since 2018*.* As of 2019, seaweed represented 30% of marine aquaculture.
[src:autotroph/algae] In 2023, the global seaweed extract market was valued at $16.5 billion, with strong projected growth.
[src:autotroph/algae] Seaweed farming is a carbon negative crop, with a high potential for climate change mitigation.
[src:autotroph/algae] The IPCC Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate recommends "further research attention" as a mitigation tactic.
[src:autotroph/algae] World Wildlife Fund, Oceans 2050, and The Nature Conservancy publicly support expanded seaweed cultivation.
[src:autotroph/algae] An algae bioreactor is used for cultivating micro or macroalgae.
[src:autotroph/algae] Algae may be cultivated for the purposes of biomass production (as in a seaweed cultivator), wastewater treatment, CO2 fixation, or aquarium/pond filtration in the form of an algae scrubber.
[src:autotroph/algae] Algae bioreactors vary widely in design, falling broadly into two categories: open reactors and enclosed reactors.
[src:autotroph/algae] Open reactors are exposed to the atmosphere while enclosed reactors, also commonly called photobioreactors, are isolated to varying extents from the atmosphere.
[src:autotroph/algae] Specifically, algae bioreactors can be used to produce fuels such as biodiesel and bioethanol, to generate animal feed, or to reduce pollutants such as NOx and CO2 in flue gases of power plants.
[src:autotroph/algae] Fundamentally, this kind of bioreactor is based on the photosynthetic reaction, which is performed by the chlorophyll-containing algae itself using dissolved carbon dioxide and sunlight.
[src:autotroph/algae] The carbon dioxide is dispersed into the reactor fluid to make it accessible to the algae.
[src:autotroph/algae] The bioreactor has to be made out of transparent material.
[src:autotroph/algae] To be competitive and independent from fluctuating support from (local) policy on the long run, biofuels should equal or beat the cost level of fossil fuels.
[src:autotroph/algae] Here, algae-based fuels hold great promise, directly related to the potential to produce more biomass per unit area in a year than any other form of biomass.
[src:autotroph/algae] The break-even point for algae-based biofuels is estimated to occur by 2025.
[src:autotroph/algae] Today, algae are used by humans in many ways; for example, as fertilizers, soil conditioners, and livestock feed.
[src:autotroph/algae] Aquatic and microscopic species are cultured in clear tanks or ponds and are either harvested or used to treat effluents pumped through the ponds.
[src:autotroph/algae] Algaculture on a large scale is an important type of aquaculture in some places.
[src:autotroph/algae] Maerl is commonly used as a soil conditioner.
[src:autotroph/algae] Algae are used as foods in many countries: China consumes more than 70 species, including *fat choy*, a cyanobacterium considered a vegetable; Japan, over 20 species such as *nori* and *aonori*; Ireland, dulse; Chile, cochayuyo.
[src:autotroph/algae] Laver is used to make laverbread in Wales, where it is known as *bara lawr*.
[src:autotroph/algae] In Korea, green laver is used to make *gim*.
[src:autotroph/algae] The oils from some algae have high levels of unsaturated fatty acids.
[src:autotroph/algae] Some varieties of algae favored by vegetarianism and veganism contain the long-chain, essential omega-3 fatty acids, docosahexaenoic acid (DHA) and eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA).
[src:autotroph/algae] Fish oil contains the omega-3 fatty acids, but the original source is algae (microalgae in particular), which are eaten by marine life such as copepods and are passed up the food chain.
[src:autotroph/algae] The natural pigments (carotenoids and chlorophylls) produced by algae can be used as alternatives to chemical dyes and coloring agents.
[src:autotroph/algae] Carrageenan, from the red alga *Chondrus crispus*, is used as a thickener and stabilizer in milk products.
[src:autotroph/algae] Agar, a gelatinous substance derived from red algae, has a number of commercial uses.
[src:autotroph/algae] It is a good medium on which to grow bacteria and fungi, as most microorganisms cannot digest agar.
[src:autotroph/algae] Alginic acid, or alginate, is extracted from brown algae.
[src:autotroph/algae] Its uses range from gelling agents in food, to medical dressings.
[src:autotroph/algae] Alginic acid also has been used in the field of biotechnology as a biocompatible medium for cell encapsulation and cell immobilization.
[src:autotroph/algae] Molecular cuisine is also a user of the substance for its gelling properties, by which it becomes a delivery vehicle for flavours.
[src:autotroph/algae] Between 100,000 and 170,000 wet tons of *Macrocystis* are harvested annually in New Mexico for alginate extraction and abalone feed.
[src:autotroph/algae] Agricultural Research Service scientists found that 60–90% of nitrogen runoff and 70–100% of phosphorus runoff can be captured from manure effluents using a horizontal algae scrubber, also called an algal turf scrubber (ATS).
[src:autotroph/algae] Scientists developed the ATS, which consists of shallow, 30-metre (100 ft) raceways of nylon netting where algae colonies can form, and studied its efficacy for three years.
[src:autotroph/algae] They found that algae can readily be used to reduce the nutrient runoff from agricultural fields and increase the quality of water flowing into rivers, streams, and oceans.
[src:autotroph/algae] Researchers collected and dried the nutrient-rich algae from the ATS and studied its potential as an organic fertilizer.
[src:autotroph/algae] They found that cucumber and corn seedlings grew just as well using ATS organic fertilizer as they did with commercial fertilizers.
[src:autotroph/algae] Algae scrubbers, using bubbling upflow or vertical waterfall versions, are now also being used to filter aquaria and ponds.
[src:autotroph/algae] The alga *Stichococcus bacillaris* has been seen to colonize silicone resins used at archaeological sites; biodegrading the synthetic substance.
[src:autotroph/algae] Various polymers can be created from algae, which can be especially useful in the creation of bioplastics.
[src:autotroph/algae] These include hybrid plastics, cellulose-based plastics, poly-lactic acid, and bio-polyethylene.
[src:autotroph/algae] Several companies have begun to produce algae polymers commercially, including for use in flip-flops and in surf boards.
[src:autotroph/algae] Even algae is also used to prepare various polymeric resins suitable for coating applications.
[src:autotroph/algae] The third island on Kunming Lake at Beijing's Summer Palace is called Zaojian Tang Dao (藻鑒堂島).
[src:autotroph/autotroph] An **autotroph** is an organism that can convert abiotic sources of energy into energy stored in organic compounds, which can be used by other organisms.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Autotrophs produce complex organic compounds (such as carbohydrates, fats, and proteins) using carbon from simple substances such as carbon dioxide, generally using energy from light or inorganic chemical reactions.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Autotrophs do not need a living source of carbon or energy, and are the producers in a food chain, such as plants on land or algae in water.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Autotrophs can reduce carbon dioxide to make organic compounds for biosynthesis and as stored chemical fuel.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Most autotrophs use water as the reducing agent, but some can use other hydrogen compounds such as hydrogen sulfide.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Autotrophs use a portion of the ATP produced during photosynthesis or the oxidation of chemical compounds to reduce NADP+ to NADPH to form organic compounds.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Primary producers are at the lowest trophic level, and are the reasons why Earth sustains life to this day.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Photoautotrophs convert the energy of light into chemical energy through photosynthesis, ultimately building organic molecules from carbon dioxide, an inorganic carbon source.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Chemolithotrophs produce biomass from the oxidation of inorganic chemical compounds; they are frequently found in hydrothermal vents in the deep ocean and include some archaea and bacteria (unicellular organisms).
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Most chemoautotrophs are lithotrophs, using inorganic electron donors such as hydrogen sulfide, hydrogen gas, elemental sulfur, ammonium, and ferrous oxide as reducing agents; and hydrogen sources for biosynthesis and chemical energy release.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Chemolithoautotrophs are microorganisms that synthesize energy through the oxidation of inorganic compounds.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] They can sustain themselves entirely on atmospheric CO2 and inorganic chemicals without the need for light or organic compounds.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] They enzymatically catalyze redox reactions using mineral substrates to generate ATP energy.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] These substrates primarily include hydrogen, iron, nitrogen, and sulfur.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Its ecological niche is often specialized to extreme environments, including deep marine hydrothermal vents, stratified sediment, and acidic hot springs.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Some organisms rely on organic compounds as a source of carbon, but can use light or inorganic compounds as a source of energy.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] An organism that obtains carbon from organic compounds but obtains energy from light is called a *photoheterotroph*, while an organism that obtains carbon from organic compounds and energy from the oxidation of inorganic compounds is termed a *chemolithoheterotroph*.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Evidence suggests that some fungi may also obtain energy from ionizing radiation: Such radiotrophic fungi were found growing inside a reactor of the Chernobyl nuclear power plant.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] The term *autotroph* was coined by the German botanist Albert Bernhard Frank in 1892.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] It stems from the ancient Greek word τροφή (*trophḗ*), meaning "nourishment" or "food".
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Without primary producers, organisms that are capable of producing energy on their own, the biological systems of Earth would be unable to sustain themselves.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Plants, along with other primary producers, produce the energy that other living beings consume, and the oxygen that they breathe.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] It is thought that the first organisms on Earth were primary producers located on the ocean floor.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Autotrophs are fundamental to the food chains of all ecosystems in the world.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] They take energy from the environment in the form of sunlight or inorganic chemicals and use it to create fuel molecules such as carbohydrates.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] This mechanism is called primary production.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Other organisms, called heterotrophs, take in autotrophs as food to carry out functions necessary for their life.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Thus, heterotrophs – all animals, almost all fungi, and most bacteria and protozoa – depend on autotrophs, or primary producers, for the raw materials and fuel they need.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Heterotrophs obtain energy by breaking down carbohydrates or oxidizing organic molecules (carbohydrates, fats, and proteins) obtained in food.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Carnivorous organisms rely on autotrophs indirectly, as the nutrients obtained from their heterotrophic prey come from autotrophs they have consumed.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Most ecosystems are supported by the autotrophic primary production of plants and cyanobacteria that capture photons initially released by the sun.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Plants can only use a fraction (approximately 1%) of this energy for photosynthesis.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] The process of photosynthesis splits a water molecule (H2O), releasing oxygen (O2) into the atmosphere, and reducing carbon dioxide (CO2) to release hydrogen atoms that fuel the metabolic process of primary production.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Plants convert and store the energy of the photons into the chemical bonds of simple sugars during photosynthesis.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] These plant sugars are polymerized for storage as long-chain carbohydrates, such as starch and cellulose; glucose is also used to make fats and proteins.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] When autotrophs are eaten by heterotrophs, i.e., consumers such as animals, the carbohydrates, fats, and proteins contained in them become energy sources for the heterotrophs.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Proteins can be made using nitrates, sulfates, and phosphates in the soil.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Aquatic algae are a significant contributor to food webs in tropical rivers and streams.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] This is displayed by net primary production, a fundamental ecological process that reflects the amount of carbon that is synthesized within an ecosystem.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] This carbon ultimately becomes available to consumers.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Net primary production displays that the rates of in-stream primary production in tropical regions are at least an order of magnitude greater than in similar temperate systems.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Researchers believe that the first cellular lifeforms were not heterotrophs as they would rely upon autotrophs since organic substrates delivered from space were either too heterogeneous to support microbial growth or too reduced to be fermented.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Instead, they consider that the first cells were autotrophs.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] These autotrophs might have been thermophilic and anaerobic chemolithoautotrophs that lived at deep sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] This view is supported by phylogenetic evidence – the physiology and habitat of the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) is inferred to have also been a thermophilic anaerobe with a Wood-Ljungdahl pathway, its biochemistry was replete with FeS clusters and radical reaction mechanisms.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] The high concentration of K+ present within the cytosol of most life forms suggests that early cellular life had Na+/H+ antiporters or possibly symporters.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Autotrophs possibly evolved into heterotrophs when they were at low H2 partial pressures where the first form of heterotrophy were likely amino acid and clostridial type purine fermentations.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] It has been suggested that photosynthesis emerged in the presence of faint near-infrared light emitted by hydrothermal vents.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] The first photochemically active pigments are then thought to be Zn-tetrapyrroles.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] The first autotrophic organisms likely evolved early in the Archean but proliferated across Earth's Great Oxidation Event with an increase to the rate of oxygenic photosynthesis by cyanobacteria.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Photoautotrophs evolved from heterotrophic bacteria by developing photosynthesis.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] The earliest photosynthetic bacteria used hydrogen sulfide.
[src:autotroph/autotroph] Due to the scarcity of hydrogen sulfide, some photosynthetic bacteria evolved to use water in photosynthesis, leading to cyanobacteria.
